<br>
His pet, Gebaner, sat dutifully by his side, constantly on the alert for danger to his master. The mage sat, secure in the knowledge that he is protected. The pet knows only of his duty and his alertness is a comfort to both parties. But as time passed, Gebaner’s mind (what there is of it) began to wander. It is not often that he is allowed to sit quietly for such an extended period.<br>
<br>
Gebaner turned to Grafire and asked “Where do I come from?”<br>
<br>
Grafire leapt to his feet, dagger at the ready, his hands already starting to cast a destructive spell. “Who’s attacking!” he yelled.<br>
<br>
Gebaner repeated his question. “Where do I come from?” <br>
<br>
Grafire looked to his small brown friend and said, “Oh, you’re talking. Sorry. I thought we were under attack. You usually only talk when there’s trouble.&quot; Grafire sat down and began to sort his equipment again, a slightly embarrassed flush on his face.<br>
<br>
“What did you ask?”<br>
<br>
“Where do I come from?”<br>
<br>
“Oh, uh… that’s an odd one. Why do you ask?”<br>
<br>
“I don’t know. It just came to me. I’ve been sitting here thinking.” <br>
<br>
Grafire paused to stare at Gebaner. “Thinking eh? That’s just about as dangerous for you as wandering Befallen with out me. Or with me for that matter.”<br>
<br>
Grafire straightened up and turned to face Gebaner. “So … where do you come from, eh? Hmmmm.”<br>
<br>
“Well, you see Gebaner, when a mommy dirt clod and a daddy dirt clod really love each other … no, that’s not going to work. Uh … under the leaves in the cabbage patches that the Druids grow …. No, it covers the dirt angle, but that’s just stupid. There’s this thing called a stamen … and the bird gets his foot … the pollen sticks to a … but then a bee comes along…. Oh hell, I never understood that whole story anyway.”<br>
<br>
Grafire looked around nervously, twiddling spiderling silks between his fingers.<br>
<br>
“When two malachite stones love each other … no, it only takes one.”<br>
<br>
“When one malachite stone loves itself … uh … no, that’s getting a little too ‘personal’.”<br>
<br>
“I guess when it comes right down to it, I just create you.” Grafire finally admitted.<br>
<br>
“Then you’re my mommy?” Gebaner queried.<br>
<br>
“Well, I prefer daddy. But yes, I guess it works out like that.” Grafire said, turning back to making silk bandages.<br>
<br>
“Do you give birth to me?” Gebaner continued.<br>
<br>
“Wha?… ewwww, no!” Grafire sputtered out. “How would I give birth to you?”<br>
Gebaner stated “Well, it might not be so hard. It’s not like I have a full set of body parts. No head and no legs, just a floating torso.”<br>
<br>
“But you’re all shoulders! And at least three feet wide! You might get away with shooting down an Ogre birth canal, but no way are you’re coming out of me! Heck, everyone knows us High Elves are the most uptight race around. Do you really think we’d spew forth mulch men or fire creatures from our loins?”<br>
<br>
“A High Elf chick gave me a fire creature in my loins one time.” Said a passing wood elf guard.<br>
<br>
“Quiet you!” Grafire shouted back.<br>
<br>
He returned his attention to the now puzzled Gebaner. “You see Gebaner, it’s kind of complicated.”<br>
<br>
“Why?” asked Gebaner.<br>
<br>
“Well, I’m still fairly new at this and I don’t know what all goes behind the process.” Grafire said apologetically.<br>
<br>
“Why?”<br>
<br>
“Because I’ve only cast pets a few times. It’s still mysterious to me.” Grafire seemed to be losing some of his patience.<br>
<br>
“But why?”<br>
<br>
“It’s just one of those mysteries of life.” said Grafire in an obvious state of annoyance.<br>
<br>
“But Wh…”<br>
<br>
“PET GO AWAY!” Grafire shouted.<br>
<br>
At that Gebaner disappeared and a silence once again fell across Kelethin. Grafire then stood up and pulled a malachite stone from his pocket and started to incant a spell. Almost immediately a stocky, flaming torso appeared next to him.<br>
<br>
Grafire once again sat down, blanketed in the warming glow of his new fiery friend. But before taking needle to thread once again, he turned to his companion and said “You, burny fellow, where do you come from?” <br>
<br>
“I don’t know. Never thought about it.” The new creature replied.<br>
<br>
“That’ll do pet. That’ll do.” Grafire said with no small amount of satisfaction and got back to the tailoring task at hand.<br>
<br>
The end.<br>
